          <msContents>
            <summary>Manuscript is used for public or private recitation or prayer and worship (pūjā), venerating and praising a thousand names associated with the Hindu deity Śiva. Manuscript is part of a larger work known as the Śivarahasya. Presented as a discourse of the deity Skanda (known also as Kārttikeya), the son of Śiva.</summary>
            <textLang mainLang="san">In Sanskrit</textLang>
            <msItem>
              <title>Śivanāmasahasra</title>
              <title type="vernacular">शिवनामसहस्र</title>
              <colophon>Colophon: iti śrīśivarahasye sadāśivākhyena vamāṃśeśeṣāśeṣamukhodgītaṃ śrīśivanāmasahasraṃ saṃpūrṇam // saṃvat 1967 vaiśākhaśu[bhe] 10 // śrīkāśīviśveśvarārpaṇam astu // śrī // tatsadbrahmārpaṇam astu // (f. 10v).</colophon>
